[OT2020] Lithiase: UML, Schema & Instance

ALDP

28/09/2020

Definition of relevant fields

Based on our literature review, examples of report result for urolithiasis and expert validation, we determined the list of relevant fields.

We determined items that are mandatory for any radiological report, as the patient identification [name, first name, birthdate, NIR (Numéro d’Inscription au Répertoire)], the protocol characteristic containing information about the imaging device and the exam, the radiologist identification and the conclusion. We detailed the device information with the device model and year of initial commissioning. For exam information we proposed to define the type of exam, it can be CT scan or US, the date and time of the exam, and the indication or clinical context (acute flank pain or lithiasis follow-up).

We determined others items about conditions for performing the urolithiasis imaging. We distinguished enhanced CT scan and NCCT, the use of low dose CT scan or not, exam performed during an acute situation or not, presence of fever, presence of urinary tract diversion. We also informed about the radiation dose expressed in milligray multiplied by centimeter (mGy.cm).

For the results, we established relevant fields such as the description of others organs than urinary tract, the presence of another abnormalitiy, the number of urolithiasis, a detailed description of each urinary tract and of each urinary stone. For the description for each organ (liver, adrenals, pancreas, spleen, ovaries and bladder) we left the possibility to describe the abnormality, the other abnormality concerned pneumoperitoneum or intraperitoneal effusion or abnormal lymph nodes or pelvic phlebolith presence. Specifically in our case, we described the presence of urinary tract abnormality, of urinary tract diversion or renal transplant. Then we informed about the number of lithiasis.

We described the urinary tract by lateralization and diversion and for each of its component elements proposed to measure the diameter or volume, to indicate the presence of hematuria, urinoma, pelviureteric junction and pyelonephritis sign.

Finally, we determined items that should be reported for each stone. It contains the stone lateralization (left, right, upper left in case of duplication, lower left, upper right, lower right), the stone size (defined by the greatest measure of diameter and expressed in millimeters), the stone location (in kidney, proximal ureter or distal ureter depending on above or below the iliac vessels, and bladder) and the stone density (expressed in HU). We specified the consequences of lithiasis, with the item obstruction and its implication.

Import du fichier .yaml

On importe le fichier .yaml à l’aide de la fonction read_yaml() issue du package yaml

A noter, la fonction read_yaml() ne gère pas la métadonnée des deux premières lignes:

%YAML 1.2
---
report_lithiase <- read_yaml(file='ot2020_lithiase.instance.yaml', fileEncoding = "UTF-8")

La fonction read_yaml() va creer un objet de type liste contenant -entre autres- des listes

Problème:

  • On s’attend à obtenir 3 valeurs par variables : 3 lithiases à décrire = 3 valeurs de lithiasis_id, 3 valeurs de lateralisation etc…
  • Or on observe -pour chaque variable de la liste- 3 variables successives dans le dataframe, contenant chacune 1 valeur

Import du fichier .yaml “condensé”

report_lithiase_condensed <- read_yaml(file='ot2020_lithiase_condensed.instance.yaml', fileEncoding = "UTF-8")

QRCode

Encodage du fichier d’instance YAML dans un QRCode à l’aide de la librairie python python-qrcode appelée avec la ligne de commande suivante

A noter que l’on fixe le niveau de redondance du code à 7% (“L”)

less instance.yaml | qr --error-correction=L > instance.png

Instance sérialisée en yaml, encodée dans un QRCode

Template

Mr/Ms {patient_name} {patient_first_name}
Date of birth {patient_birth}
Date of exam {exam_date_time}
Exam type {exam_type}
Radiologist {physician}

Exam

Indication: {exam_indication}

Conditions: {exam_type}, {device_model} {device_date}, {condition_contrast}, {condition_low_dose}, made in {condition_acute}, with{condition_fever} and with {condition_derivation}.
PDL: {condition_radiation}.

Results:

General results

{if abnormal_liver = “No”}
No liver abdnormality.
{else}
The liver presents {abnormal_liver: comments}

{if abnormal_pancreas = “No”}
No pancreas abdnormality.
{else}
The pancreas presents {abnormal_pancreas: comments}

(…)

Urinary tract

{foreach urinary_tract_results as utr}

  • {[utr]lateralization} kidney:

    • Measuring {renal_height}cm long and {renal_volume}cm3
    • {if [utr]diversion <>= “No”}
    • No urinary tract diversion.
    • {else}
    • Presence of a urinary tract diversion: {[utr]diversion}
    • {if [utr]pyelocaliceal_dilatation = “No}”
    • No pyelocaliceal dilatation
    • {else}
    • Pyelocaliceal dilatation with a interlabial pelvic diameter of {interlabial_pelvic_diameter}mm.

Lithiasis

{foreach lithiasis_results as lr}
Lithiasis {[lr]location} {[lr]lateralization} of {[lr]size}mm and density of {[lr]density} HU,
{if [lr]obstruction = “No”}
Non obstructive.
{else}
obstructive

Conclusion:

{findings}

{if further_imaging <> No}
Need for {further_imaging_type}

{if further_physician <> No}
Need for {further_physician_type} opinion advice

Dr.{physician}
